        <hr noshade size="2" color="#545A7D">
        
         This is what he said...<BR><BLOCKQUOTE id=quote><font size=2 face="Verdana" id=quote>quote:<hr height=1 noshade id=quote><BR>Yes - That was the downside. Each copy of a DoT takes up its own slot, due to duration, focus, and damage credit differences. <BR><hr height=1 noshade id=quote></BLOCKQUOTE id=quote></font id=quote><font face="Verdana" size=2 id=quote></P><P>What I take from that is that DoT's being cast at different times is the primary problem.  NecroA casts pyro on tick 1 and NecroB casts pyro on tick 3 of a fight.  The game engine cannot keep track of those two DoT's in the same slot cause they have different time elements.  Now...if the two DoT's were cast at the same time...</P><P>The extension effects affect the same problem.  As the DoT's will wear off at different times, they must occupy different slots to be tracked properly.</P><P><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=157918" target=new>Ishtarra Gemeinseele </a><BR>Warlock of the Dirty Soul<BR>Uber N00b Extraordinaire<BR>Tunare Server</P><P>edit...also, the engine cannot distinguish who is responsible for the DoT's if stacked in the same slot.  So, the first necro who cast the spell would get the credit for all the damage being done by all spells in that slot.  </P><P>All in all, it seems that the slots are one dimensional or a single layer.  For us to get DoT stacking where each spell takes up one slot, regardless of how many instances of the spell are cast, would require the slots to be multilayered/multi-dimensional...whatever you want to call it.  I would prefer calling it the Matrix.  LOL!!</P><P>Edited by - ishtarra on 08/22/2002  14:28:48<a href="#top"><img src="icon_go_up.gif" height="15" width="15" border="0" align="right" alt="Go to Top of Page"></a></font></td>
